<Layout title="Mental Health & Psychiatric Assessment Tools" description="Mental health and psychiatric assessment tools used in nursing">
  <a href={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}/`} class="back-link">← Back to all categories</a>
  <div class="badge">Mental Health &amp; Psychiatric</div>
  <h1>Mental Health &amp; Psychiatric Assessment Tools</h1>
  <p>Validated instruments for screening and assessing depression, anxiety, psychosis, PTSD, suicide risk, and other mental health conditions.</p>

  <div class="tool-list">
    <h2>Assessment Tools</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>PHQ-2 (Patient Health Questionnaire-2)</strong> — Two-item depression screening tool. Score ≥3 warrants full PHQ-9 evaluation. Used in primary care and general nursing settings.</li>
      <li><strong>PHQ-9 (Patient Health Questionnaire-9)</strong> — Nine-item DSM-based depression severity scale. Score 0–27: 5–9 mild, 10–14 moderate, 15–19 moderately severe, 20–27 severe depression.</li>
      <li><strong>GAD-7 (Generalized Anxiety Disorder 7-item)</strong> — Self-report anxiety scale. Score 0–21: 5 mild, 10 moderate, 15 severe. Also screens for panic disorder, social anxiety, and PTSD.</li>
      <li><strong>C-SSRS (Columbia Suicide Severity Rating Scale)</strong> — Gold-standard suicide risk assessment measuring ideation (1–5 severity) and behavior (actual attempts, preparatory acts, self-injury).</li>
      <li><strong>SADPERSONS Scale</strong> — Ten-item suicide risk mnemonic: Sex, Age, Depression, Previous attempt, Ethanol use, Rational thinking loss, Social support lacking, Organized plan, No spouse, Sickness. Guides disposition decisions.</li>
      <li><strong>BAI (Beck Anxiety Inventory)</strong> — 21-item self-report anxiety severity scale; distinguishes anxiety from depression. Score 0–63: 0–7 minimal, 8–15 mild, 16–25 moderate, 26–63 severe.</li>
      <li><strong>BDI (Beck Depression Inventory)</strong> — 21-item self-report depression scale. Score 0–63: 0–13 minimal, 14–19 mild, 20–28 moderate, 29–63 severe depression.</li>
      <li><strong>HAM-A (Hamilton Anxiety Rating Scale)</strong> — 14-item clinician-rated anxiety scale; assesses psychic and somatic anxiety. Score &lt;17 mild, 18–24 moderate, 25–30 severe.</li>
      <li><strong>HAM-D (Hamilton Depression Rating Scale)</strong> — 17-item clinician-administered depression scale. Score 0–7 normal; 8–13 mild; 14–18 moderate; 19–22 severe; &gt;23 very severe.</li>
      <li><strong>BPRS (Brief Psychiatric Rating Scale)</strong> — 18-item clinician-rated scale for psychopathology severity across multiple domains; widely used in psychosis research and monitoring.</li>
      <li><strong>PANSS (Positive and Negative Syndrome Scale)</strong> — 30-item scale for psychosis severity in schizophrenia. Scores positive, negative, and general psychopathology subscales.</li>
      <li><strong>MMPI-2 (Minnesota Multiphasic Personality Inventory-2)</strong> — 567-item comprehensive personality and psychopathology assessment; produces validity scales and 10 clinical scales. Requires trained interpretation.</li>
      <li><strong>PCL-5 (PTSD Checklist for DSM-5)</strong> — 20-item self-report PTSD symptom scale aligned with DSM-5 criteria. Score ≥33 suggests probable PTSD diagnosis.</li>
      <li><strong>Davidson Trauma Scale</strong> — 17-item self-report PTSD frequency and severity measure based on DSM-IV criteria; used in research and clinical settings.</li>
      <li><strong>IES-R (Impact of Event Scale-Revised)</strong> — 22-item self-report of PTSD symptom clusters: intrusion, avoidance, and hyperarousal. Score ≥33 suggests PTSD diagnosis.</li>
      <li><strong>MDQ (Mood Disorder Questionnaire)</strong> — 13-item self-report bipolar disorder screening tool. Positive screen: ≥7 items endorsed, symptoms occurring together, causing moderate-severe problems.</li>
      <li><strong>YMRS (Young Mania Rating Scale)</strong> — 11-item clinician-rated mania severity scale. Score 0–12 normal; 13–19 minimal; 20–25 mild; 26–37 moderate; 38–60 severe mania.</li>
      <li><strong>Y-BOCS (Yale-Brown Obsessive Compulsive Scale)</strong> — 10-item clinician-rated OCD severity scale measuring obsession and compulsion subscores (0–20 each). Total 0–40.</li>
      <li><strong>ACEs Questionnaire (Adverse Childhood Experiences)</strong> — Ten-item screen for childhood abuse, neglect, and household dysfunction. Score 0–10; higher ACE scores correlate with adverse health outcomes throughout life.</li>
      <li><strong>GDS (Geriatric Depression Scale)</strong> — 15 or 30-item yes/no depression screening tool validated for older adults. Short form score ≥5 suggests depression.</li>
      <li><strong>Cornell Scale for Depression in Dementia</strong> — 19-item clinician-rated tool using caregiver interviews and patient observation to assess depression in cognitively impaired patients.</li>
      <li><strong>EPDS (Edinburgh Postnatal Depression Scale)</strong> — 10-item self-report screen for postpartum depression. Score ≥13 (or any score on item 10 for self-harm) warrants clinical follow-up.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</Layout>
